  "notes": "Old Saxon (~800–1100 CE). Ancestor of Low German (Plattdeutsch). Major text: Heliand (~830 CE) — a Saxon gospel harmony in alliterative verse. NO HIGH GERMAN CONSONANT SHIFT: OS p, t, k unchanged (cf. OHG pf/ff, tz/ss, hh). OS makōn vs. OHG mahhōn 'to make'; OS water vs. OHG wazzer 'water'. Closely related to Old English and Old Frisian (all Ingvaeonic). Preserved þ as interdental, like OE. Source: Gallée (1993), Robinson (1992).",
